1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,599
Charles Darwin made what might be the most important scientific discovery of all time,

2
00:00:09,199 --> 00:00:11,500
the theory of evolution by natural selection.

3
00:00:12,480 --> 00:00:20,390
It was Darwin who first understood how it was that plants and animals evolved over time to produce new and different species.

4
00:00:21,440 --> 00:00:26,350
At first, this theory faced much opposition, but since that time,

5
00:00:26,350 --> 00:00:29,149
it has been supported by evidence from many areas of science.

6
00:00:31,079 --> 00:00:34,539
Darwin was born in a small town in England in 1809.

7
00:00:35,840 --> 00:00:37,729
When he was a young man, he went to university,

8
00:00:38,899 --> 00:00:42,149
first to study medicine and later to study religion.

9
00:00:42,700 --> 00:00:45,969
However, Darwin found his schoolwork to be very boring.

10
00:00:46,880 --> 00:00:47,439
Instead,

11
00:00:47,439 --> 00:00:51,439
he preferred outdoor activities and was very interested in nature.

12
00:00:52,399 --> 00:00:54,259
While Darwin was at university,

13
00:00:56,079 --> 00:01:01,600
the British Navy was planning to send one of its ships called the Beagle on a voyage of exploration.

14
00:01:02,280 --> 00:01:03,619
As part of this voyage,

15
00:01:03,619 --> 00:01:08,969
the ship would need a naturalist who could study the various plants and animals that might be found.

16
00:01:09,879 --> 00:01:13,049
Darwin was recommended for this job by one of his professors,

17
00:01:13,049 --> 00:01:15,150
who had been impressed by Darwin.

18
00:01:16,099 --> 00:01:18,939
Darwin was chosen as the naturalist of the Beagle,

19
00:01:18,939 --> 00:01:21,939
and the ship left England in 1831.

20
00:01:22,840 --> 00:01:24,609
The ship's voyage took Darwin around the world,

21
00:01:25,319 --> 00:01:28,939
and he observed many species of plants and animals on his trip.

22
00:01:29,939 --> 00:01:33,500
In one place near South America, known as the Galapagos Islands,

23
00:01:34,700 --> 00:01:36,989
Darwin observed many unusual species of birds.

24
00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:41,030
Several of these birds seemed closely related to each other,

25
00:01:41,799 --> 00:01:43,469
but they differed in interesting ways.

26
00:01:44,319 --> 00:01:44,950
For example,

27
00:01:44,950 --> 00:01:49,250
some birds had long beaks that could reach insects hidden in the bark of trees,

28
00:01:50,379 --> 00:01:53,670
but other birds had thick beaks that could break open the shells of nuts.

29
00:01:55,099 --> 00:02:00,140
What Darwin realized was that certain characteristics could help an animal or a plant to survive and reproduce.

30
00:02:03,099 --> 00:02:07,209
Individuals that lacked those characteristics would become more likely to die without reproducing.

31
00:02:09,439 --> 00:02:10,639
Over many generations,

32
00:02:10,639 --> 00:02:17,810
the useful characteristics would then become more and more common as the surviving individuals passed the characteristics on to their offspring.

33
00:02:19,840 --> 00:02:21,210
Eventually, after many generations,

34
00:02:21,210 --> 00:02:26,280
the changes would be so great that a new species would exist.

35
00:02:26,620 --> 00:02:30,669
In this way, a single species could divide into two or more new ones.

36
00:02:32,020 --> 00:02:34,659
This was called the process of evolution by natural selection.

37
00:02:36,460 --> 00:02:38,150
When Darwin returned to England,

38
00:02:38,150 --> 00:02:40,280
he studied plants and animals in more detail.

39
00:02:42,240 --> 00:02:43,580
After much research,

40
00:02:43,580 --> 00:02:47,219
he began writing a book about his theory of evolution by natural selection.

41
00:02:48,319 --> 00:02:52,180
When the book The Origin of Species was published in 1859,

42
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:54,280
it was very popular.

43
00:02:54,659 --> 00:02:56,069
It was very popular and very controversial.

44
00:02:56,680 --> 00:03:00,050
During the next 20 years, Darwin continued his scientific research,

45
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:03,330
and he wrote several more books.

46
00:03:03,919 --> 00:03:06,110
By the time of his death in 1882,

47
00:03:06,900 --> 00:03:12,860
many biologists had realized that Darwin had made one of the most important scientific discoveries of all time.

48
00:03:13,780 --> 00:03:14,969
For the first time,

49
00:03:14,969 --> 00:03:18,949
scientists could understand the origin of the many different species of plants and animals.

